I talked with Crispin Cowan <crispin@cse.ogi.edu>, one of the StackGuard[K
developers and he proposed a remediation against above hack.  Here's his idea:[K
The XOR Random Canary defense:  here, we adopt Aaron Grier's ancient[K
proposal to xor the random canary with the return address.  The canary[K
validation code used on exit from functions then XOR's the return address[K
with the proper random canary (assigned to this function at exec() time)[K
to compute what the recorded random canary on the stack should be.  If the[K
attacker has hacked the return address, then the xor'd random canary will[K
not match.  The attacker cannot compute the canary to put on the stack[K
without knowing the random canary value.  This is effectively encryption[K
of the return address with the random canary for this function.[K
The challenge here is to keep the attacker from learning the random[K
canary value.  Previously, we had proposed to do that by just surrounding[K
the canary table with red pages, so that buffer overflows could not be[K
used to extract canary values.  However, Emsi's [described above] attack[K
lets him synthesize pointers to arbitrary addresses.[K
